SUMMARY: A Love Letter to Handsome John (2026)
DESCRIPTION:After its Sold Out Premier in Indianapolis\, IN\, A Love Lett
 er To Handsome John (2026) travels down the highway to Bloomington for a 
 one-night only screening at The BCT.\n\nAn intimate portrait of Todd Snid
 er in the last year of his life.\nWhat starts as a film about gratitude\,
  and a way to say thank you to John Prine\, becomes a rare glimpse of the
  artist at home in his most quietest moments.\n\nMORE INFO: https://otisg
 ibbs.com/a-love-letter-to-handsome-john-by-otis-gibbs/ https://otisgibbs.
 com/a-love-letter-to-handsome-john-by-otis-gibbs/\n\nRating: N/A\nFormat:
  DCP\nLength: 54 Minutes\n\nFilmaker Otis Gibbs is a songwriter\, storyte
 ller\, painter\, photographer\, and planter of 7\,176 trees. He once wres
 tled a bear and lost. He’s been called “the best unknown songwriter in mu
 sic today\,” but if you ask him\, he’ll just say he’s a folksinger.\n\nTh
 e Trust Of Crows\, his tenth studio album\, was recorded at the iconic Co
 lumbia Studio A in Nashville\, where Bob Dylan made Blonde on Blonde and 
 Nashville Skyline. It’s been closed to the public for decades\, but Otis 
 was given permission to record there.\n\nGibbs’ storytelling extends beyo
 nd music to his YouTube channel\, where more than 100\,000 subscribers li
 sten to tales and folklore passed down by legendary musicians. In an effo
 rt to preserve these personal stories before they’re lost to history\, he
  single handedly built a living archive in the spirit of The Lomax Family
 \, Studs Terkel or even Charles Kuralt. This deeply personal project refl
 ects Otis’ reverence for history\, lived experience\, and the characters 
 who shaped American roots music from the ground up.\n\nOtis embraced a DI
 Y ethic early on\, sometimes by choice and sometimes out of necessity. Wh
 ether it’s starting his own record label\, podcast\, YouTube channel\, or
  whatever else needed to be done\, he’s created his own ecosystem in the 
 arts—all while wearing the same work shirt and old felt hat that he wore 
 planting trees 25 years ago. He continues to shine a light on the forgott
 en people\, places\, and the unvarnished beauty of everyday life.
CATEGORIES:Bloomington,Film,In-Person,Music
